---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageIntro from "../components/PageIntro.astro";
import RelatedLinks from "../components/RelatedLinks.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="Meet Kamatamare Sanuki, Kagawa's local J.League football club."
>
  <PageIntro
    eyebrow="Meet Kagawa's local football club"
    title="About Kamatamare Sanuki"
    description="A welcoming J.League club with a name, identity, and story rooted in Kagawa."
  />
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="container container--narrow prose">
      <h2>Kagawa's only J.League club</h2>
      <p>
        Kamatamare Sanuki is the only J.League football club in Kagawa Prefecture. Its hometown
        covers the whole prefecture, with particularly strong connections to Takamatsu and
        Marugame.
      </p>
      <p>
        Watching a home match is a chance to enjoy professional Japanese football and experience
        a local side of Kagawa that many overseas visitors do not see.
      </p>

      <h2>What does “Kamatamare Sanuki” mean?</h2>
      <p>
        The club's unusual name comes directly from the region:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><strong>Kamatama</strong> comes from <em>kamatama udon</em>, a popular Kagawa dish.</li>
        <li><strong>Mare</strong> means “sea” in Italian, recalling the nearby Seto Inland Sea.</li>
        <li><strong>Sanuki</strong> is the historic name of the area now known as Kagawa.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Together, the name connects the club with Kagawa's food, landscape, and local identity.
      </p>

      <h2>Rooted in the community</h2>
      <p>
        Kamatamare Sanuki sees itself as a community-based club for all of Kagawa. Its activities
        extend beyond the professional team to youth development, football schools, local events,
        and projects with communities across the prefecture.
      </p>
      <p>
        At a home match, you may see families, long-time supporters, local volunteers, and people
        attending for the first time. The atmosphere reflects the close relationship between the
        club and the region it represents.
      </p>

      <h2>Your first match is welcome</h2>
      <p>
        You do not need to know every player, understand every chant, or speak Japanese to enjoy
        the match. It is completely fine to watch quietly, learn as you go, and simply take in
        the atmosphere.
      </p>
      <p>
        Arrive early, keep your ticket ready, and ask a member of staff if you are unsure where
        to go. A Kamatamare match can be an easy and memorable addition to your Kagawa trip,
        whether you come alone, with friends, or with family.
      </p>

      <h2>Plan your visit with this guide</h2>
      <p>
        This independent English guide explains the basic information that overseas visitors may
        need before their first match:
      </p>
      <ol class="check-list">
        <li>Read <a href="/history/">Club History</a> for the club's short timeline.</li>
        <li>Use <a href="/stadium/">Stadium & Access</a> to prepare your journey.</li>
        <li>Check the <a href="/faq/">FAQ</a> for practical first-visit answers.</li>
        <li>Confirm all current details on the official club website before travelling.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="official-box">
        <h2>Independent and unofficial</h2>
        <p>
          This is a personal fan-made guide. It is not produced, approved, or operated by
          Kamatamare Sanuki, the J.League, the stadium, or a local government.
        </p>
        <p>
          Match dates, kick-off times, tickets, transport, player information, and stadium rules
          can change. If this guide differs from an official announcement, follow the official
          information.
        </p>
        <p>
          <a
            class="text-link"
            href="https://www.kamatamare.jp/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer">Visit the official Kamatamare Sanuki website</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <RelatedLinks
    links={[
      {
        label: "Club History",
        href: "/history/",
        description: "Meet the club and learn the meaning behind its name.",
      },
      {
        label: "Stadium & Access",
        href: "/stadium/",
        description: "Plan a less stressful journey to your first home match.",
      },
      {
        label: "Frequently Asked Questions",
        href: "/faq/",
        description: "Find quick answers about tickets, language, food, and more.",
      },
    ]}
  />
</BaseLayout>
